In our first set of experiments for 3-party FL-HPO (p=3ğ‘3p=3), we compare our proposed scheme with the baseline across different datasets, machine learning models and FLoRA loss surfaces. The aggregated results are presented in TableÂ 1, with the individual results detailed in AppendixÂ C.3. For each of the three methods, we report the aggregate performance over all considered datasets in terms of (i)Â inter-quartile range, (ii)Â Wins/Ties/Losses of FLoRA w.r.t. the single-shot baseline, and (iii)Â a one-sided Wilcoxon Signed Ranked Test of statistical significance with the null hypothesis that the median of the difference between the single-shot baseline and FLoRA is positive against the alternative that the difference is negative (implying FLoRA improves over the baseline). Finally, we also report an â€œOverallâ€ performance, further aggregated across all ML models.

While in the previous experiment, we studied the effect of the thoroughness of the local HPO runs on the performance of FLoRA, here we consider a subtly different setup. We assume that each party performs T=100ğ‘‡100T=100 rounds of local asynchronous HPO. However, instead of sending all Tğ‘‡T (HP, loss) pairs, we consider sending Tâ€²<Tsuperscriptğ‘‡â€²ğ‘‡T^{\prime}<T of the â€œbestâ€ (HP, loss) pairs â€“ that is, (HP, loss) pairs with the Tâ€²superscriptğ‘‡â€²T^{\prime} lowest losses. Changing the value of Tâ€²superscriptğ‘‡â€²T^{\prime} trades off the communication overhead of the FLoRA step where the aggregators collect the per-party loss pairs (AlgorithmÂ 1, line 5). We consider 2 datasets each for 2 of the methods (SVM, MLP) and all the loss surfaces for FLoRA, and report all the results in TableÂ 10.

The results for all the methods and datasets are aggregated in TableÂ 8. All FLoRA loss surfaces show strong performance with respect to the single-shot baseline, with significantly more wins than losses, and 3rd-quartile regret values less than 1 (indicating improvement over the baseline). All FLoRA loss surfaces have a p-value of less than 0.050.050.05, indicating that we can reject the null hypothesis.

MPLM appears to have the worst performance but much of that is attributable to the really high regret of 6.8 and 2.84 it received for SVM with Heart Statlog and Pollen (both hard cases as discussed earlier). Otherwise, MPLM performs second best both for FL-HPO with HGB and MLP.
